{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"963afb94-196e-4078-8e18-039c6da03643","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect the trace (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope**.\n\n**4. Copy it out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use **`DOTNET_EventPipe`** environment variables to collect a trace on startup instead.\n- For production, prefer `dotnet-monitor` as a sidecar — it exposes a REST API to collect traces without exec.\n- Convert to speedscope format for browser-based analysis: `dotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d4e18a78-6755-46ed-96c2-94f602b8aedf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, practical advice.","outputTokens":381,"requestId":"4197:70BC2:635049E:6C62C25:69F15EBA"},"id":"1290a341-e3e9-48d6-84a5-2f1920c024ce","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:28:35.302Z","parentId":"d51973e6-10f3-4899-b44a-e72c438c0925"}
